{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2e4ee4e9-5e26-47f5-8314-6c7d0aa4c8cc","content":"Here are the **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n---\n\n**1. File I/O Property Function (line 13, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n`ReadAllText` runs during *evaluation* — before any build targets execute. File I/O in property functions is expensive and blocks the evaluation pipeline. Move this into a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs during execution.\n\n**2. Expensive Glob Pattern (line 9, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the *entire* directory tree. As the repo grows (especially if `node_modules`, `.git`, or large asset dirs exist), this glob becomes increasingly costly. Narrow it to specific extensions/subdirectories, or add costly paths to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n**3. Deep Import Chain (3 levels)**\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds to evaluation time. Here it's 3 levels (tolerable), but this pattern can easily grow past 20+ levels in real repos. Prefer flattening imports or consolidating into `Directory.Build.props` at the repo root.\n\n---\n\n**Recommended fixes (priority order):**\n1. Remove the `File::ReadAllText` call — read the file in a build target instead.\n2. Replace `**\\*.*` with a targeted glob like `**\\*.txt` or scope to a specific folder.\n3. Keep the import chain shallow; consolidate settings where possible.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"976caf82-9dd0-4aea-9c5e-c2d1c9d0a33d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a clear picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues.","outputTokens":466,"requestId":"0403:28D016:6326E41:6BFBCEE:69F01083"},"id":"193f9fb6-06f6-442a-a7d6-4d4f19d2e05d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:42:40.038Z","parentId":"5594581e-094f-4f3c-b3f5-b1c0dcd04711"}
